	<p>
		<term>Section 1: Ionic compounds</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		To review, compounds are pure substances that consist of atoms of various elements that are joined together in a specific ratio. There are two different classes of compounds: ionic compounds and covalent/molecular compounds. In this section, we’ll be learning about the differences between ionic compounds and covalent compounds. What distinguishes ionic compounds from covalent/molecular compounds is the way in which the atoms are joined together.
	</p>

	<p>
		<term>Ionic compounds</term> are made up of <term>ions</term> that are joined together by <term>electrostatic forces</term>. Ions are particles that have a net charge, either a positive or a negative charge. Ions can either be positively charged (<term>cations</term>) or negatively charges (<term>anions</term>). Additionally, ions can either consist of one atom (a monoatomic ion) or of several atoms that are joined together to form a larger charged unit (a polyatomic ion). An ionic compound consists of cations and anions that are held together because their opposite charges attract one another (electrostatic forces).
	</p>

	<p>
		<term>Covalent compounds</term> (also known as <term>molecular compounds</term>) are formed from atoms that are joined together by sharing electrons. Ionic compounds always consist of multiple ions, which are separate units that are attracted to one another. In contrast, covalent compounds consist of a single unit that is comprised of all of the component atoms. Within this unit, the atoms are held together by the sharing of electrons. This unit of a covalent compound is called a <term>molecule</term>.
	</p>

	<p>
		Ionic compounds generally (but not always…we’ll learn about the exceptions later) consist of a metal and one or more non-metals. Covalent compounds, on the other hand, consist exclusively of non-metals. This can be useful in allowing us to identify whether a compound is an ionic or covalent compound. Recall that metals can be found on the left side of the periodic table whereas non-metals can be found exclusively on the upper right. Thus, if a compound contains a metal, we can be confident that it is an ionic compound. If a compound doesn’t contain a metal, it is usually a covalent compound (again, we’ll learn about exceptions to this in a later section).
	</p>

	<p>
		These atomic-level differences between ionic and covalent compounds lead to very different physical properties. The physical properties that we’ll be learning about are melting point and behavior in solution. In general, ionic compounds have much higher melting points than covalent compounds. In a solid ionic compound, the ions are held together by strong electrostatic forces as we learned above. In a solid covalent compound, the various molecules are themselves held together, but by much weaker <term>intermolecular forces</term>. We’ll discuss intermolecular forces in much more detail later in this chapter. Since the forces that hold together ions in an ionic compound are much stronger than the intermolecular forces that hold together molecules in a covalent compound, more energy is required to break the bonds in an ionic compound. This results in a higher melting point.
	</p>

	<p>
		There is a big difference between ionic and covalent compounds when it comes to how they can dissolve in water to form a solution. When an ionic compound dissolves in water, the electrostatic interactions between the ions are replaced by interactions between the ions and water. Basically, the ions that make up the ionic compound separate from one another and get surrounded by water molecules. When covalent compounds dissolve in water, they remain as intact molecules. Each molecule is surrounded by water molecules similar to what is seen for an ionic compound. The difference is that molecules remain intact whereas the ions that make up ionic compounds separate from one another.
	</p>

