	<p>
		<term>Section 2: Ions</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		In this section, we’ll be learning about how atoms form ions. First of all, what is an ion. We’ve learned that an ion is a species that is charged. So how does it get its charge? It does so by having extra electrons or by lacking electrons. If an atom has more electrons than protons, then its charge will be negative and it will be an anion. If an atom has fewer electrons than protons, then the atom will be positively charges, and it will be a cation. Importantly, the number of protons will NEVER change for an element. Ions are created by either adding or removing electrons.
	</p>

	<p>
		Why do some atoms gain electrons whereas other atoms lose them? Why do some gain/lose a single electron whereas others gain/lose multiple? To understand this, we need to revisit electron configurations. The most stable elements on the periodic table are the noble gases. Why are they so stable? It turns out that they are stable because their orbitals are either completely filled or completely empty! For instance, the electron configuration of helium is <m>1s^{2}</m> and the electron configuration of neon is <m>1s^{2}2s^{2}2p^{6}</m> (recall that a set of s-orbitals hold 2 electrons, a set of p orbitals can hold 6…etc.). For all of the noble gases except helium, they have 8 <term>valence electrons</term> (helium has 2). Thus the most stable electron configurations will have 8 valence electrons, something known as the <term>octet rule</term>.
	</p>

	<p>
		For many elements, they form ions in order to get an electron configuration that is the same as a noble gas. For instance, if a group 1 metal loses a single electron, then it will have the same electron configuration as a noble gas (ex. the electron configuration of sodium is <m>\lbrack Ne\rbrack 3s^{1}</m> and if it loses its outermost valence electron then its electron configuration will simply be <m>\lbrack Ne\rbrack 3s^{0}</m> or simply <m>\lbrack Ne\rbrack</m>). Because of this, group 1 metals tend to lose a single electron to form ions. Elements in group 2 tend to lose 2 electrons, because this will give them an electron configuration that is the same as a noble gas as well. On the other side of the periodic table, the halogens (group 17 or 7A) have electron configurations that are a single electron away from resembling a noble gas. In order for them to reach a noble gas configuration, they have to GAIN one electron. As a result they’ll form negatively charged anions. Elements in group 16 will likewise gain two electrons to achieve a noble gas electron configuration.
	</p>

	<p>
		Many of the elements in the periodic table have predictable charges in ionic compounds. The metals in group 1 will always have a +1 charge. The metals in group 2 will always have a +2 charge. Aluminum will likewise always have a +3 charge. The halogens (group 17 or 7A) will always for anions with a -1 charge. The non-metals in group 16 (6A) will gain two electrons to form -2 anions. The non-metals in group 15 (5A), nitrogen and phosphorus, can gain 3 electrons to form -3 anions. Hydrogen is a rather unique element, in that it can lose one electron (forming a +1 ion with completely empty orbitals) or gain an electron to resemble helium (forming a -1 anion).
	</p>

