	<p>
		<term>Section 3: Simple ionic compounds</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		Ionic compounds are formed by combining cations and anions. When they are combined, they must do so in such a way that the total positive charge is equal to the total negative charge. Sometimes this is simple. For instance a <m>Na^{+}</m> ion can be combined with a <m>Cl^{-}</m> ion in a 1:1 ratio because the +1 charge from the sodium balances the -1 charge from the chlorine. There would therefore be one of each ion in the <term>chemical formula</term> for this compound, and we’d write it simply as <m>NaCl</m> (note: if there’s one of an element in a chemical formula the 1 is not written). On the other hand, if we wanted to make an ionic compound by joining a <m>Ca^{2 +}</m> ion with a <m>Cl^{-}</m> ion, then we’d require 2 <m>Cl^{-}</m> ions to balance the +2 charge on the calcium ion. Thus, they’d combine to form the compound <m>CaCl_{2}</m> (the number of ions is written as a subscript). <em>Also, note that when we write the chemical formula of an ionic compound that we don’t include the charges of the ions!</em>
	</p>

	<p>
		Ionic compounds can be specified by their chemical formula (as covered above) or by their name. How do we name ionic compounds? Naming ionic compounds is easy. They consist of two separate words. The first word is the name of the cation, and the second word is the name of the anion. For simple ionic compounds that have metal cations with known charges, naming the cation is easy…it’s simply the name of that metal. The name of the anion is more complex. To name the anion, we start with the name of the element, but we delete the ending of the name and replace it with -ide. See the table below:
	</p>

