	<p>
		Thus the name of <m>NaCl</m> is sodium chloride and <m>CaBr_{2}</m> would be calcium bromide. When we’re naming ionic compounds, we NEVER use prefixes to indicate the number of ions present. The number of ions is implied by our knowledge about the ions themselves and their charges. To illustrate this, lets figure out the chemical formula for magnesium oxide. We know that this compound consists of magnesium and oxygen. Based on their locations in the periodic table, we can conclude that magnesium would form a +2 ion and that oxygen would form a -2 ion. In order to get the positive and negative charges to balance, we’d need a 1:1 ratio so the correct formula would simply be <m>MgO</m>.
	</p>

